          "body": "The chapter opens with a rhetorical flourish: who is like the wise man, and who knows the interpretation of a matter? (8:1). The question does not assume no one is wise — it celebrates the rarity and value of wisdom by asking us to think of someone who actually possesses it. The answer, implied, is the person Qohelet is addressing. Wisdom does something visible: it illumines the face, transforms the stern countenance. Then immediately Qohelet grounds wisdom in a practical test case — the royal court. The counsel of vv. 2-9 is profoundly practical: keep the king's command because of the oath before God (8:2), do not rashly leave his presence, do not join an evil cause (8:3), for his word is authoritative and he does whatever he pleases (8:4). This is not sycophancy; it is the wisdom of Proverbs' court instruction applied to a situation where power is real and consequences are severe. The wise man's advantage is named in verse 5: he 'knows the proper time and procedure' (et u-mishpat). He can read the situation, wait for the right moment, act with the appropriate method. But verses 6-7 immediately qualify this: there is indeed a proper time and procedure — but no one knows in advance what will happen, or when. The wise man's practical advantage (knowing timing) is set within an epistemic limit (not knowing the future). And verse 8 closes the section with the three things no one has authority over: the wind, the day of death, and the soldier's discharge in wartime — the last of which serves as analogy: you are enrolled in a war you did not choose, subject to forces you cannot dismiss. The section ends with Qohelet's blunt summary (8:9): all the exercise of human authority over other humans tends toward those humans' hurt."
